(Principle
    "Cluster data should de-emphasize booleans. Optional capabilities should appear as vectors of named feature variants, with data-carrying variants when inline feature configuration is genuinely part of the cluster dial."
    "I don't want to emphasize booleans. Because then we read the cluster data, it just says true or false. ... instead, you might as well just have a vector of features. And if we have different kinds of features, we have different kinds of vectors. But then it just becomes a variant name. So by reading the cluster data, we can see, oh yeah, this thing has a Gitolite server. ... Booleans should be de-emphasized, essentially. And a variant naming the feature should be used instead in a vector of features. And those variants can be even data-holding variants."
    "Direction while resuming the Horizon redesign after production Horizon and CriomOS cluster-data cleanup. Production lessons should apply to the new Horizon shape: cluster data is readable role/capability selection, while derived ports, domains, and standardized configuration belong in Horizon reduction or CriomOS."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T12:26:44Z)

(Principle
    "Cluster data favors data-carrying variants over booleans. When a node carries a capability, name the capability as a variant in a feature vector; let the variant carry whatever inline tuning is genuinely part of the cluster dial. Reading the cluster file should reveal role and capability selection directly — `(GitoliteServer …)` not `gitoliteEnabled = true`."
    "I would really like the cluster data to be very clean, and emphasize variants with possibly data carrying variants if a little bit of tuning can be done."
    "Restating the variants-over-booleans direction (originally 2026-05-19T12:26:44Z) during the Logix/Horizon lean-rewrite analysis kickoff, with the additional emphasis on data-carrying variants where inline tuning is part of the dial."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20 14:50)

(Principle
    "Cluster data must not embed anything that isn't actually being configured. Port numbers, derived addresses, well-known constants, and any value that an out-of-the-box standardized component already implies should not appear in the cluster description. Components are becoming standardized; if a component just works, the cluster data only names that the node carries it, not how it is wired."
    "I don't want anything like port numbers and specific details that don't actually need to be configured, because we're creating an easy to reason about system where components are just becoming standardized. The Git server, for example, will just be made to work out of the box…"
    "Direction during the Logix/Horizon lean-rewrite analysis kickoff. Cluster data is dial-shaped: what role the node plays and what features it carries — not the operational constants that follow from those choices."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20 14:50)

(Principle
    "The cluster relies on Yggdrasil-style unique per-node IP addresses. Routing tables bootstrap dynamically from those identities, so the cluster description does not need to embed routing details, peer endpoints, or transport ports — peers find each other through the routing substrate. Workspace-wide assumption that informs every component contract: addressing is not a cluster-data concern."
    "we have things like unique IP addresses with the Yggdrasil routing system, and then these can be used to bootstrap a routing table dynamically. So there's no need to embed all of this stuff in the cluster configuration."
    "Foundational network-substrate assumption stated during the Logix/Horizon lean-rewrite analysis. Justifies removing routing/endpoint material from cluster data."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20 14:50)

(Clarification
    "Network interface names currently appearing in cluster data are a short-term hack. The right shape is for a future network daemon to discover interfaces and pick a role per device dynamically; until that daemon exists, the cluster file has to carry interface names so deploy can wire the system. Treat the interface-name fields as temporary; do not deepen them or build dependent abstractions around their permanence."
    "currently we, it's a hack, right, it's a short term hack, but we have things like network interface names in the cluster data, because I haven't taken the time to actually develop a system whereby … But right now we don't have that daemon, that type of daemon doesn't exist. So we just put the interface names in the cluster data, just because we have to."
    "Marking the production-and-lean cluster data's interface-name fields as transitional during the Logix/Horizon lean-rewrite analysis kickoff."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20 14:50)

(Decision
    "Eventual future: a dedicated network daemon discovers connectivity and assigns interface roles dynamically. The daemon figures out where its internet connection comes from (a Wi-Fi access point one day, a LAN interface the next, etc.) and distributes that connection across other interfaces. Not addressed now; named so the cluster-data shape can be designed knowing this is the destination. Until the daemon ships, cluster data carries the interface-name hack."
    "we're going to have to develop our own network daemon, eventually, not now, so that the daemon is intelligent enough to try and get an internet connection from something, whatever it is, and it could be different at every point. Maybe some days it actually gets the internet from a Wi-Fi access point, and then distributes that connection to its LAN interfaces, and maybe another day it's the other way around, or it gets an internet connection from one of its LAN interface, and then it distributes it downstream from the other LAN interfaces as well as its Wi-Fi interface."
    "Naming the future network-daemon destination during the Logix/Horizon lean-rewrite analysis kickoff. Justifies why cluster data should not grow further interface/topology fields."
    Medium
    2026-05-20 14:50)

(Principle
    "Eventually, cluster data is very minimal. The destination shape: which type of node is this, plus disk configuration (which disk to boot from, where each filesystem lives, where the boot partition sits). Disk configuration is the last genuinely convoluted thing expected to remain; maybe even that goes away one day. Drive every design choice on the lean rewrite toward this minimal destination."
    "we want to try and minimize, essentially, eventually the cluster data will be just like, actually very minimal. Just like what type of node is this, maybe the last really convoluted looking things that are going to be left in the cluster data is things like disk configuration, like to know which disk to boot from, and where the file system for such and such part of the system is installed, where the boot partition is, like that's as complicated as we really need to get, and maybe even one day there's a way to take that out."
    "Naming the cluster-data destination during the Logix/Horizon lean-rewrite analysis. Sets the directional target for every shape choice in the lean rewrite."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20 14:50)

(Principle
    "Horizon's job is to lower cluster data into something easy for Nix code to consume. Horizon is the pure-data reduction layer, not a place to put operational constants. Keep Horizon's logic clean and small; do not pollute it with port numbers, DNS server lists, domain-construction recipes, or other constants that belong wherever consumes them. The Nix code happily holds those constants today; that is where they live."
    "And then the horizon lowers this into something that is easy for Nixcode to consume. But at the same time, I don't want the horizon to do everything. We don't need to put all these constants like port numbers, and how to construct such and such domain name into the horizon. Like it's not that hard to put these constants in the Nixcode, that way we keep the horizon more simple."
    "Setting Horizon's scope during the lean-rewrite analysis kickoff. Horizon = lower cluster intent to Nix-consumable form; constants stay in the consumer."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20 14:50)

(Principle
    "Prefer beautiful Horizon over beautiful Nix code. If a constant or piece of operational glue has to live somewhere ugly, the ugliness goes in Nix, not in Horizon. Horizon is meant to be elegant and small; Nix code is the bootstrap substrate that will eventually be replaced. Optimising Nix code's beauty at Horizon's expense is the wrong trade."
    "I would way rather make the horizon code more beautiful and keep some of this dirty stuff like port numbers into the Nixcode. And all these constants, like which name servers we use for name resolution on the public internet and so on. That can stay in Nix."
    "Direction during the Logix/Horizon lean-rewrite analysis kickoff. Establishes which side of the split absorbs unavoidable ugliness."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20 14:50)

(Principle
    "Horizon must not duplicate data types between input and output when the value is just passed through. Reuse the input type at the output position; only introduce a distinct output type when the lowering genuinely transforms shape. Duplicate types for passthrough values are pure code expansion with no information gain."
    "I think there's a lot of data type duplication between input and output, and there's no need for that to actually be. We can reuse these data types if they're just passed through."
    "Pointed at as a concrete gap during the Logix/Horizon lean-rewrite analysis kickoff. Direct guidance for the new horizon code shape."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20 14:50)

(Decision
    "View-side derived predicates (the 16 booleans on view::Node + BehavesAs in horizon-rs lean) move out of horizon. Derivation lives Nix-side in a single shared location — likely CriomOS-lib — so each consuming Nix module reads the same predicate definitions instead of horizon emitting them. Horizon stays a clean projector; CriomOS-lib carries the let-bindings that turn variants (species, placement, size, trust, arch) into the predicate booleans Nix modules gate on."
    "derive them in a single location nix-side (criomos-lib?)"
    "Psyche answer to the §8.2 derived-predicate question in reports/system-assistant/26. Settles direction: remove all 16 predicates from horizon; consolidate derivation in CriomOS-lib (or whichever shared Nix-lib home best fits). Question mark on the exact location indicates CriomOS-lib is the leading candidate, not the final decision."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20 15:30)

(Decision
    "Fold the 4 bare booleans on NodeProposal (nordvpn, wifi_cert, wants_printing, wants_hw_video_accel) into the NodeService vector as additional named variants (Nordvpn, WpaEnterpriseClient, Printing, HardwareVideoAccel). Cluster data emits a single feature vector; the 4 bool positions on NodeProposal retire."
    "Fold four bare booleans into node service. Yes."
    "Psyche answer to Q1 in reports/system-assistant/29. Recommended one-list (unified fold) lands; sibling-vector alternative dropped."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20T18:31:00Z)

(Decision
    "online: Option<bool> drops from NodeProposal entirely. Runtime reachability belongs in lojix-daemon's believed-topology state (intent/deploy.nota 2026-05-17T11:00:00Z); cluster intent does not encode it. The existing administratively-offline escape hatch goes away with the drop; if that state becomes load-bearing before lojix's believed-topology query exists, a typed variant will be added then."
    "Online, yeah, drop, drop online."
    "Psyche answer to Q2 in reports/system-assistant/29. Operational state cleanly out of cluster data."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20T18:31:00Z)

(Decision
    "view::BuilderConfig drops entirely from horizon-rs. Horizon no longer constructs per-builder records; Nix iterates horizon.exNodes filtering on a Nix-derived nodeIsRemoteNixBuilder predicate and builds the nix.buildMachines attrset directly from per-node typed data (criome_domain_name, system, max_jobs, ssh pubkey). The boolean-check + value-mapping work is cheap Nix-side."
    "View builder config collapse entirely. Or keep a leaner version. Yeah, drop it. Let's clean up the horizon. This is cheap to do in Nix anyway. It's just a bunch of like boolean checks and like value mapping or whatever."
    "Psyche answer to Q3 in reports/system-assistant/29. Cleanup discipline reaffirmed: work that is cheap Nix-side belongs Nix-side, not in horizon."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20T18:31:00Z)

(Decision
    "HorizonProposal.transitional_ipv4_lan retires from Rust entirely. The IPv4 LAN constants (cidr, gateway, dhcp_pool) move into CriomOS-lib constants with a large warning comment; the warning string disappears from any record (a Nix comment carries it). Clusters do not share internal IPv4 addressing in the destination shape (IPv6-first via Yggdrasil); the workspace has one cluster (LiGoldragon's), so per-cluster handling is unnecessary. The whole HorizonProposal record may shrink to operator + domain_suffixes + trusted_keys only."
    "Horizon proposal, transitional IPv4 LAN. Well, I don't see why it needs to be per cluster. It's not like, these clusters aren't going to talk anyway. … just fucking hard code this in Nix. Let's just keep this bullshit out of our Rust code. … there's only one cluster right now. Mine. So we don't need to worry about it. Just, we're going to comment. We're going to put a big warning red light comment over that."
    "Psyche answer to Q4 in reports/system-assistant/29. Drops the field from HorizonProposal; constants move to CriomOS-lib with red-light warning."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20T18:31:00Z)

(Decision
    "NodeProposal field order: placement promotes from the last position to position 2, immediately after species. The placement variant (Metal vs Contained) is a load-bearing description of what kind of node this is — bare metal vs contained — and belongs visually alongside species at the head of the record. New order: species, placement, size, trust, machine, io, pub_keys, …. All downstream positional consumers (datom.nota, fixtures, projector code) update."
    "this variant metal, which I guess has the other variant, which is pod, it should go higher because it's kind of like a pretty important part of what this is. So it's probably like after edge testing, after the species would be metal. And then large, max, and so on."
    "Psyche reordering during reports/system-assistant/29 review. The 'pod' phrasing is the psyche guessing at the second variant's name — current name is Contained; whether to rename Contained → Pod is a separate open question."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20T18:31:00Z)

(Decision
    "wireguard joins NodePubKeys alongside ssh, nix, and yggdrasil. The wireguard sub-record (pub_key + untrusted_proxies, per the grouping decision in this report's prior review) lives inside NodePubKeys, not as a separate field on NodeProposal. NodePubKeys becomes the canonical home for every per-node key bundle including mesh-membership sub-records (yggdrasil already inside; wireguard joining). The agent has latitude on the wireguard sub-record's internal shape."
    "the wire guard thing. Why don't we put the wire guard key with all of the other keys? You can think about that."
    "Psyche direction during reports/system-assistant/29 review. Implementation latitude granted on whether untrusted_proxies stays inside the wireguard sub-record or moves elsewhere."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20T18:31:00Z)

(Decision
    "Brainstorm direction: derive a per-node wireguard internal IP address from the wireguard public key, kind of like Yggdrasil derives its address from its pub key. If this works in practice, node_ip drops from NodeProposal entirely and the wireguard interface IP plus allowedIPs become functions of the wireguard pub key Nix-side. Open concern flagged by psyche: routing-table interaction — Yggdrasil's IP-from-key works because the whole protocol is built around it; for Wireguard the derivation is a workspace convention, not protocol-level. Brainstorm only, do not deep-dive."
    "I'd rather derive some kind of IP address from the wire guard public key, kind of like how Yggdrasil does it. I just don't know how well this will do for like a routing table and stuff. So I don't know. You can maybe brainstorm a little bit on that, but don't spend too much time on it."
    "Psyche-flagged brainstorm direction during reports/system-assistant/29 review. Conservative certainty (Minimum) reflects the explicit uncertainty about routing-table feasibility."
    Minimum
    2026-05-20T18:31:00Z)

(Decision
    "NodePlacement variant rename: Contained → Pod. The psyche prefers 'Pod' over 'Contained' because it reads more naturally as a noun (a contained node IS a pod inside its host) and is shorter. Prior naming convention from Nathan was 'Contained'; the rename supersedes that. Updated identifier set: NodePlacement::Metal | NodePlacement::Pod { host, user, substrate, resources, network, state, trust, user_namespace_policy }."
    "Nathan said we should call it contained. Do you think that's a better name than pod? I don't know. I think I like pod."
    "Psyche soft-preference (Medium certainty, hedged with 'I don't know') during reports/system-assistant/29 review. Settles open clarification A. Rename touches NodePlacement (proposal/placement.rs), datom.nota fixtures, view re-exports, and every Nix consumer that destructures the variant."
    Medium
    2026-05-20T18:45:00Z)

(Decision
    "Wireguard internal-IP derivation from the wireguard pub key (hash-based, Yggdrasil-style) is the approved direction; implementation is deferred out of scope for now. Wireguard is in the code but not currently load-bearing in any deployment, so node_ip's wireguard-routing consumers (wireguard.nix:33, 61) are not actively exercised. Drop node_ip from NodeProposal and view::Node immediately. Mark the wireguard-derivation TODO with a large in-code comment at the Nix consumer sites (wireguard.nix module + CriomOS-lib) plus a horizon-rs comment noting why node_ip retired. The derivation function itself (deriveWireguardIp in CriomOS-lib) lands when Wireguard becomes load-bearing."
    "okay, so it looks like we can do a hash-based IP address for WireGuard. So we're going to do that. So we can take the node IP out. … WireGuard is in the code, but it's not useful right now. … So we can just sort of defer that hash-based IP out. That's out of scope for now, but we can mark that in the report as why we're taking it out and maybe put a comment in the code where the WireGuard IP address should go, and like a big to-do. So we can take out this node IP."
    "Psyche resolving the wireguard-IP brainstorm (intent/horizon.nota 2026-05-20T18:31:00Z). Direction approved; implementation deferred; node_ip drops now because the wireguard consumer path isn't load-bearing today. Updates the prior Minimum-certainty brainstorm record to settled Maximum direction."
    Maximum
    2026-05-20T18:45:00Z)

(Decision
    "Brainstorm direction (psyche-flagged, not settled): router-ness moves from NodeSpecies into the NodeService vector as a data-carrying variant Router(RouterInterfaces). Today router-ness is dual-encoded — in species (Router, Hybrid, LargeAiRouter, RouterTesting variants) and in the standalone NodeProposal.router_interfaces field. The proposal folds the router-interfaces data inside the services variant and lets species drop its router-flavored variants (Router, Hybrid, LargeAiRouter, RouterTesting), leaving species = 'kind of cluster member' (Center, Edge, LargeAi, CloudHost, EdgeTesting, MediaBroadcast, Publication) and services = 'what specific things this node does'. Explicit psyche uncertainty: 'Just an idea, it might actually be cleaner. I don't know'."
    "the router interfaces. So how do we currently define if a node is a router? Is it just a species? Or do we put that into the feature vector? In which case, the router interfaces could be the data of that particular variant in the feature vector. Just an idea, it might actually be cleaner. I don't know"
    "Psyche-flagged brainstorm during reports/system-assistant/29 review. Conservative certainty (Minimum) reflects the explicit hedge. If approved, species and services become orthogonal — species describes kind, services describes capabilities; the variants-over-booleans principle applied to enum compounding."
    Minimum
    2026-05-20T18:45:00Z)
